The well-known pas- sage in St. Bernard's Life of St. Malachi, con- cerning the church of Bangor, proves that the Scotic attachment to wooden churches contin- ued in Irelaud to the twelfth century, and that though stone churches existed, they were regarded as os foreign introduction. See the able disquisition on this subject in Dr. Petrie's Essay on the Round Towers, pp. 122-154.
